\begin_layout Section
SI units
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Physics is a natural science.
 One of the key objectives of physics is to predict the future or outcome
 of events.
 It is a known fact that the laws of nature can be discovered and put up
 as simple relations of formulae using the language of Mathematics.
 The process of discovery of laws follows the steps of observation, measurements
 and finding the patterns.
 The repeating pattern itself become the laws.
 This can be termed as the scientific method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key step in any natural science is the idea of measurement.
 When we want to describe a phenomena or an event, it usually involves descripti
on of a physical quantity in terms of a number and the number is obtained
 through the process of measurement.
 For example if we want to describe a room, we could give its length, breadth
 and height, all of which will require measurements of length.
 In measurement we compare the physical quantity with a given standard size
 of the physical quantity which we call the unit of that physical quantity.
 In the measurement of the length of room we compare the length with the
 standard size-metre of the length and if we find that the room is 20 m
 long only means that the standard metre is contained 20 times in the total
 length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In nature we find that there are only a certain minimum number of quantities
 that we need to measure, all the rest can be described in terms of this
 minimum set of physical quantities.
 These are traditionally called the fundamental physical quantities and
 the units of these fundamental quantities are called fundamental or base
 units.
 In old times only length, mass and time were considered as fundamental
 and various countries and kings followed different sets of units for these.
 This often led to confusions and sometimes also critical accidents when
 not properly converted from one set of units to the other.
 In SI system of units there are seven quantities defined as the fundamental
 or base quantities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

