\begin_layout Standard
All the quantities which are obtained as some combination of the base quantities
 are known as the derived quantities.
 Examples of derived quantities are force, velocity, acceleration, pressure,
 energy etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Uncertainty/Errors in measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The complete statement of a measured value should include an estimate of
 the level of confidence associated with the value.
 Properly reporting an experimental result along with its uncertainty allows
 other people to make judgments about the quality of the experiment and
 it facilitates meaningful comparisons with other similar values or a theoretica
l prediction.
 Without an estimated uncertainty, it would be impossible to answer the
 basic scientific questions such as: “Does my result agree with theoretical
 prediction or results from other experiments?” This question is fundamental
 for deciding if a scientific hypothesis is to be confirmed or refuted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we make a measurement, it is generally assumed that there exists a
 true value for any physical quantity being measured.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
every measurement is approximate due to errors in measurement.
 In general, the errors in measurement can be broadly classified as (a)
 systematic errors and (b) random errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Systematic errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The systematic errors are those errors that tend to be in one direction,
 either positive or negative.
 Some of the sources of systematic errors are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Instrumental errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that arise from the errors due to imperfect design or calibration of the
 measuring instrument, zero error in the instrument, etc.
 For example, the temperature graduations of a thermometer may be inadequately
 calibrated (it may read 104 °C at the boiling point of water at STP whereas
 it should read 100 °C); in a vernier callipers the zero mark of vernier
 scale may not coincide with the zero mark of the main scale, or simply
 an ordinary metre scale may be worn off at one end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Imperfection in experimental technique or procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine the temperature of a human body, a thermometer placed under
 the armpit will always give a temperature lower than the actual value of
 the body temperature.
 Other external conditions (such as changes in temperature, humidity, wind
 velocity, etc.) during the experiment may systematically affect the measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Personal errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that arise due to an individual’s bias, lack of proper setting of the apparatus
 or individual’s carelessness in taking observations without observing proper
 precautions, etc.
 For example, if you, by habit, always hold your head a bit too far to the
 right while reading the position of a needle on the scale, you will introduce
 an error due to parallax.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Systematic errors can be minimised by improving experimental techniques,
 selecting better instruments and removing personal bias as far as possible.
 For a given set-up, these errors may be estimated to a certain extent and
 the necessary corrections may be applied to the readings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random errors 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The random 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
errors are those errors, which occur irregularly and hence are random with
 respect to sign and size.
 These can arise due to random and unpredictable fluctuations in experimental
 conditions (e.g.
 unpredictable fluctuations in temperature, voltage supply, mechanical vibration
s of experimental set-ups, etc), personal (unbiased) errors by the observer
 taking readings, etc.
 For example, when the same person repeats the same observation, it is very
 likely that he may get different readings everytime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation of errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If all sources of systematic uncertainties have been identified and reduced
 to a negligible level, statistical theory says that the mean is the best
 estimation to the true value.
 In formal mathematical terms, the mean value x of a set of N measurements
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{x}=\frac{x_{1}+x_{2}+x_{3}+\cdots+x_{N}}{N}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the summation sign 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is the shorthand notation indicating the sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Absolute and mean absolute error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The magnitude of the difference between the individual measurement and the
 true value of the quantity is called the absolute error of the measurement.
 This is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 In absence of any other method of knowing true value, we considered arithmatic
 mean as the true value.
 Then the errors in the individual measurement values from the true value,
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta x_{1} & =x_{1}-\bar{x},\\
\Delta x_{2} & =x_{2}-\bar{x},\\
\ldots & \ldots\\
\Delta x_{n} & =x_{n}-\bar{x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The arithmetic mean of all the absolute errors is taken as the final or
 mean absolute error of the value of the physical quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 It is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x_{\text{mean}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Delta x}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\overline{\Delta x} & =\frac{\left|\Delta x_{1}\right|+\left|\Delta x_{2}\right|+\ldots+\left|\Delta x_{n}\right|}{n}\nonumber \\
\overline{\Delta x} & =\Sigma_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\left|\Delta x_{n}\right|}{n}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Relative and percentage error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relative error is the ratio of the mean absolute error 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\Delta x}$
\end_inset

 to the mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 of the quantity measured.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Relative error}=\frac{\overline{\Delta x}}{\bar{x}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and the percentage error is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta x=\left(\frac{\overline{\Delta x}}{\bar{x}}\right)\times100\%
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Propagation/Combination of errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a physical quantity defined as a combination of other physical quantities,
 the error in the measurement of that physical quantity will be calculated
 based on the errors of all of the physical quantities on which it depends.
 The rules for combining errors are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Errors in addition and subtraction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a physical quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 appears as the sum or difference of other physical quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=X\pm Y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 yield the values 
\begin_inset Formula $X\pm\triangle X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\pm\Delta Y$
\end_inset

 then the error in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\triangle Z=\triangle X+\triangle Y.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Errors in multiplication and division
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a physical quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 appears as the product or division of other physical quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z=X\times Y\,\,\,\text{OR}\,\,\,X/Y
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 yield the values 
\begin_inset Formula $X\pm\triangle X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\pm\Delta Y$
\end_inset

 then the fractional error in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\triangle Z}{Z}=\frac{\triangle X}{X}+\frac{\triangle Y}{Y}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Error in a physical quantity that involves powers is also calculated using
 the product rules, for example if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=A^{2}=A\times A
\]

\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\triangle Z}{Z}=2\frac{\triangle A}{A}
\]

\end_inset

or in general if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=A^{n}$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\triangle Z}{Z}=n\frac{\triangle A}{A}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Vectors and scalars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In physics we come across many different measureable quantities.
 It is observed that some quantities are plain additive for example if we
 have 1 lt of water in one pot and 2 lt in another pot, then combining them
 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2=3$
\end_inset

 lt of water.
 However this is not true in many other cases such as for example 1 banana
 and 2 apples do not equal to 3 bananas or 3 apples due to the nature of
 the fruites being different.
 Likewise in physics some quantities can be added like numbers called scalars
 whereas others require special method for addition (or subtraction); these
 are known as vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scalars are all those physical quantities whose measurement means only its
 value which is a number (with proper unit).
 Examples are temperature, pressure, volume, position, speed etc.
 Vectors are all those quantities whose measurement means not only its value
 but also its direction in space.
 The measurement of direction is a necessity in order to carry out operations
 (such as addition multiplication etc) on the physical quantity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example consider displacement of a particle.
 Suppose a particle starts from a point and moves 20 m to the east and then
 turns 
\begin_inset Formula $90^{\text{o}}$
\end_inset

 and travels further by 30 m.
 The displacement is the shortest distance between the initial and final
 points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
