\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

From the Pythagoras theorem we can calculate the displacement to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{20^{2}+30^{2}}=36$
\end_inset

 m, whereas the total distance travelled by the particle is 50 m.
 Thus displacement the way it is defined does not follow the usual rules
 of addition.
 All such physical quantities which are added like the displacement are
 termed as vector quantities.
 Thus we take displacement as a physical quantity which defines vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We often draw vector quantities on a ruled (graph) paper as directed line
 segments, where the length of the line segement is proportional to its
 magnitude and the direction is represented on paper by showing a pointed
 arrow.
 The starting point of the segment is known as the tail of vector and the
 pointed arrow is known as the head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
