\begin_layout Subsubsection
Analytical addition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} [scale=0.8]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines,color=lightgray] (0,0) grid (8,4);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [thick,-latex] (0,0) coordinate (O) -- (4.5,0) coordinate (A) node [midway,b
elow] {
\backslash
textbf{A}}; 
\backslash
draw [thick,-latex] (A) -- (7,4) coordinate (C) node [midway,left] {
\backslash
textbf{B}};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [very thick,-latex] (O) -- (C) node [midway,above,rotate=30] {$
\backslash
mathbf{C=A+B}$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [thick,dashed] (C) -- (7,0) coordinate (P) node [midway,right] {$B
\backslash
sin
\backslash
theta$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [thick,dashed] (A) -- (7,0) node [midway,below] {$B
\backslash
cos
\backslash
theta$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw pic [draw,thick,angle radius=1cm,"$
\backslash
theta$"] {angle = P--A--C}; 
\backslash
draw pic [draw,thick,angle radius=1cm,"$
\backslash
alpha$",angle eccentricity=1.3] {angle = A--O--C};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the diagram it can be easily seen that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C\cos\alpha=A+B\cos\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C\sin\alpha=B\sin\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Squaring and adding we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C^{2}=A^{2}+B^{2}+2AB\cos\theta\label{eq:analytical_magnitude}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and dividing we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tan\alpha=\frac{B\sin\theta}{A+B\cos\theta}.\label{eq:analytical_direction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytical_magnitude"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:analytical_direction"

\end_inset

 give the magnitude and direction of the resultant vector in terms of the
 magnitudes of individual vectors and the angle between them.
 The direction of the resultant vector is specified by the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 that the resultant makes with the first vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unit vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A unit vector iwith a unit magnitude is known as a unit vector.
 If we divide any vector with its magnitude we het a unit vector along its
 direction.
 A unit vector is often represented by drawing a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
tikz 
\backslash
draw (0,0) -- (0.15,1ex) -- (0.3,0);
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (known as cap or hat or carat) above the vector.
 For example a unit vector in the direction of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{A}}$
\end_inset

 and also
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{A}}=\frac{\boldsymbol{A}}{\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resolution of vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scalar and vector product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The product of vectors is also defined in a special way.
 In fact that are two types of vector multiplications.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dot product of scalar product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have two vectors say 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

 then the dot product or scalar product between the two is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{A}\cdot\boldsymbol{B}=\left|\boldsymbol{A}\right|\left|\boldsymbol{B}\right|\cos\theta=AB\cos\theta
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the smaller angle between the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The scalar product is so called because it gives a number from the multiplicati
on of vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{multicols}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Mechanics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{multicols}{2}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Concept of force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A stone falls to the ground, a cricket ball crosses boundary, a swimmer
 plunges into a swimming pool.
 What causes the movement in each of these cases? In each of these examples
 the motion is caused by a push or pull.
 We use the word 
\series bold
force
\series default
 to describe pushes and pulls.
 In all the examples above force has 
\series bold
changed the speed
\series default
 of an object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A force may change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the speed of an object
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the direction of traveling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the shape or size of an object.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Force is an interaction between two objects.
 Force is exerted by an object A on another object B.
 Force is a vector quantity and if more than one forces act on a body/particle,
 we can find the resultant using laws of vector addition.
 Various types of forces in nature can be grouped as (a) gravitational (b)
 electromagnetic (c) strong nuclear (d) weak nuclear.
 The 
\series bold
SI
\series default
 unit of force is Newton written as 
\series bold
N
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Newton's laws of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Newton's laws of motion are central in physics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
First law of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\emph on
A body remains un-accelerated (at rest or in uniform motion) if total force
 acting on it is zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically;
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{a}=0\,\,\,\,\Leftrightarrow\,\,\,\,\vec{F}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Concept of rest, motion and acceleration requires specification of frame
 of reference.
 Acceleration can be different in different frames of reference.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A frame of reference is a place from where measurements are made using different
 instruments such as a metre scale and a clock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A frame of reference in which Newton's 1st law is valid is called an inertial
 frame of reference.
 And a frame in which Newton's 1st law is not valid is called a non-inertial
 frame of reference.
 Earth for most practical purposes can be considered as an inertial frame
 of reference.
 Further all frames moving uniformly(constant velocity) with respect to
 an inertial frame are themselves inertial.
 Thus a train moving with uniform velocity w.r.t.
 ground, plane moving with uniform velocity w.r.t.
 highway are examples of inertial frames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Second law of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The acceleration of a particle is given by the resultant forces acting on
 the particle divided by its mass.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In symbols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{a}=\vec{F}/m\,\,\text{or}\,\,\vec{F}=m\vec{a}.\label{eq:2ndlaw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Momentum: The quantity of motion possessed by a body is called its momentum
 and it is measured by the product of its mass and velocity.
 In symbols
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\overrightarrow{p}}=m\vec{v}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is a vector quantity and its SI unit is 
\begin_inset Formula $kg\,m/s.$
\end_inset

 Newton's 2nd law can also be framed in terms of momentum as;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\emph on
The rate of change of momentum of a body is directly proportional to the
 impressed force and takes place in the direction of the force.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{F} & \propto & \frac{\Delta\vec{p}}{\Delta t}\\
\vec{F} & =k & \frac{\Delta\vec{p}}{\Delta t};
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where for simplicity(of the unit force) the constant of proportionality
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1.$
\end_inset

 Also
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}=\frac{\Delta\vec{p}}{\Delta t}=\frac{\Delta(m\vec{v})}{\Delta t}\label{eq:2ndlawmom}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}=m\frac{\Delta\vec{v}}{\Delta t}=m\vec{a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2ndlaw"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{F}=m\vec{a}
\]

\end_inset

the L.H.S is the cause (
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{F}$
\end_inset

) and the R.H.S.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{a}$
\end_inset

)is the effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When dealing with an event(in a physical problem), if the formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{F}$
\end_inset

 is not known one can find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{F}$
\end_inset

 by measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{a}$
\end_inset

.
 However one can predict the motion of an object in future (or in past)
 if formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{F}$
\end_inset

 is known.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2ndlaw"

\end_inset

 is therefore also known as equation of motion.
 Since it is a vector equation we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}=F_{x}\hat{i}+F_{y}\hat{j}+F_{z}\hat{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{a}=a_{x}\hat{i}+a_{y}\hat{j}+a_{z}\hat{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{p}=p_{x}\hat{i}+p_{y}\hat{j}+p_{z}\hat{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus we have from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2ndlaw"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2ndlawmom"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{x}=\frac{dp_{x}}{dt}=ma_{x},\,\,F_{y}=\frac{dp_{y}}{dt}=ma_{y},\,\,F_{z}=\frac{dp_{z}}{dt}=ma_{z}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Third law of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\emph on
To every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever a body exerts a force on another body, the second body exerts on
 the first body a force equal in magnitude but in the opposite direction.
 Forces always occur in pairs.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}_{12}=-\vec{F}_{21}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

There is no cuase-effect relationship i.e.
 action is not the cause nor is reaction the effect.
 They both co-exist.
 Also they are not acting on the same body but represent interaction between
 bodies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
noindent
\backslash
rule{1
\backslash
columnwidth}{1.0pt}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fancybreak{
\backslash
sffamily 
\backslash
textbf{Numerical Problems}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
rule{1
\backslash
columnwidth}{1.0pt}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\family sans
\series bold
Example 1:
\series default
 
\series medium
An automobile starting from rest gains a speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $60$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $km/h$
\end_inset

 after covering a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $60$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The mass of the automobile is 
\begin_inset Formula $432$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $kg$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that the air resistance and the friction, exert on the automobile
 a uniform retarding force of 
\begin_inset Formula $200$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, calculate the pull exerted by the engine.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Example 2:
\series default
 
\series medium
Calculate the resultant force on body of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $200$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $kg$
\end_inset

 moving with an acceleration of 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $m/s^{2}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Example 3:
\series default
 
\series medium
A force of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}=10\vec{i}+12\hat{j}+8\hat{k}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is acting on a block of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $kg$
\end_inset

.
 Calculate the acceleration of the particle along each of the directions.
\family default
\series default

\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fancybreak{
\backslash
rule{1
\backslash
columnwidth}{1.2pt}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conservation of momentum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}$
\end_inset

 is the external force acting on a particle, then according to Newton's
 second law of motion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{F}=\frac{d\vec{p}}{dt};
\]

\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}=0$
\end_inset

; then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\vec{p}}{dt}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and therefore we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\vec{p} & = & \text{constant}\\
\vec{p_{i}} & = & \vec{p_{f}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\emph on
When no resultant force acts on a system, the total linear momentum of the
 system remains constant in magnitude and direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This statement is called the principle of conservation of linear momentum.
 Conservation of linear momentum is a very useful tool for solving many
 mechanical problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fundamental forces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While there can be a number of forces existing on any given body, it has
 been found that there are only a handful of fundamental forces.
 All the other kinds of forces are manifestations of these fundamental forces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gravitational force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Effects of the force of gravitation are most easily observed.
 The systematic study of gravitational force was first carried out by Galileo
 and Newton.
 Newton after several experiments came up with a simple formula for gravitation.
 According to Newton
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}  % grid lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines] (-3,-3) grid (3,3);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shade [ball color=black!20] (-2.5,0) coordinate (c1) circle (0.4cm) (-2.5,0.3)
 node [anchor=south] {$m_1$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shade [ball color=black!20] (+2.5,0) coordinate (c2) circle (0.4cm) (+2.5,0.3)
 node [anchor=south] {$m_2$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [very thick,dashed,latex-latex] (c1) -- (c2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
node [below] at (0,0) {$r$};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gravitational force between two masses.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\emph on
Mass is the source of gravitational force and the force between two point
 masses 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 separated by a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is directly proportional to the product of the masses and inversely proportiona
l to the square of the distances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F & \propto & m_{1}m_{2}\,\,\text{and}\,\,F\propto\frac{1}{r^{2}}\\
F & \propto & \frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{r^{2}}\\
F & = & G\frac{m_{1}m_{2}}{r^{2}};\label{eq:gravforce}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G=6.67\times10^{-11}\,Nm^{2}/kg^{2}$
\end_inset

 is called the universal gravitational constant.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 does not change from place to place or from planet to planet and it even
 does not depend on the medium between the bodies.
 Due to the smallness of gravitational force the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is not measured with good accuracy.
 The force of gravity is only attractive, part of the reason for which is
 that there exists only one kind of mass (which is considered positive by
 convention).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force with which the earth attracts other body of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 towards itself can be given with the formula; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{F}=m\vec{g}.\label{eq:fmg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we consider earth to be a sphere of uniform density then the entire mass
 of the earth 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 can be considered to be located at its center.
 A body of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 at the surface of the earth is at a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which is equal to the radius of earth.
 In such a case by making use of formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gravforce"

\end_inset

 we can write the force between earth and the object as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=G\frac{Mm}{R^{2}}.\label{eq:earthforce}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Comparing equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fmg"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:earthforce"

\end_inset

 we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{g}=\frac{GM}{R^{2}}.\label{eq:smallg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electromagnetic force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next to the gravitational force the effects of the force which are most
 easily observed is the electromagnetic force.
 In fact the electromagnetic force is actually about 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{35}$
\end_inset

 times or more stronger than the gravitational force.
 Both electric and magnetic forces are a result of charges.
 Thus charge is the source of electric (and magnetic) force.
 Systematic study of electric and magnetic forces was carried out by several
 people; most notably Coulomb, Ampere, Faraday, Biot and Savart and their
 unification was carried out by Maxwell.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Strong and weak nuclear forces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strongest of all fundamental force is commonly referred to as the Strong
 force.
 It is responsible for binding the nucleus together.
 In fact the force that exists between protons and neutrons (not due to
 their electric charge) is called the Strong force.
 The strong force is a result of different kinds of charge called color
 charge.
 Unlike electric charge color charge exists in three flavors (red green
 and blue) and exists on smaller particles (smaller than nucleons) called
 quarks.
 Proton and neutron are made up of quarks.
 The strong force/interaction can be considered as a residual force of color
 charges.
 The strong force is attractive for distances up-to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-15}$
\end_inset

 m and becomes very small beyond that.
 This short range property is called saturation.
 The strong force is about 100 times stronger than the electromagnetic forces.
 The effects of the strong force is only observable within the nucleus(
 and some other particles known as hadrons), therefore in day to day life
 we have not encountered it directly.
 The initial systematic theoretical study of the strong force was carried
 out by Yukawa and he concluded that the force is not an inverse square
 law such as the gravity or the electromagnetic forces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand the weak force is a different type of force which is a
 result of electromagnetic forces but acts up-to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-18}$
\end_inset

 m.
 Hence this type of force is only observable in high energy experiments
 with protons and neutrons.
 The weak force is about 10,000 times weaker than the electromagnetic forces.
 The weak force/interaction is responsible for several observable phenomena
 such as beta decay.
 Further it is crucial to the structure of the universe since the sun would
 not burn without the beta decay(
\begin_inset Formula $p\to n$
\end_inset

) and the formation of heavier nuclei.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Some useful non-fundamental forces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We experience many kinds of forces in day to day life.
 All these forces are a result of the fundamental forces that we saw.
 However most forces are a result of just the electromagnetic force in one
 way or the other.
 For these forces usually a fundamental formula does not exist, however
 one can find an operational formula (one that can be used for practical
 calculations) based on experiments and events involved.
 Here we review some of the most useful forces that occur during the course
 of mechanics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Normal reaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering 
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0, every node/.style={scale=1.0}] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines,color=lightgray] (-2,-2) grid (2,2); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fill [pattern=north east lines,pattern color=black!50] (-2,-0.7) -- (2,-0.7)
 -- (2,0) -- (-2,0) -- cycle; 
\backslash
draw [very thick] (-2,0)--(2,0); 
\backslash
draw [thick,fill=black!05] (-1,0) -- (1,0) -- (1,2) -- (-1,2) -- cycle;
 
\backslash
coordinate (obj) at (0,1); 
\backslash
draw [fill] (obj) circle (2pt); 
\backslash
draw [very thick,-latex] (obj) -- +(0,2.5) coordinate (top); 
\backslash
draw [very thick,-latex] (obj) -- +(0,-2.5) coordinate (bottom); 
\backslash
node [above] at (top) {$mg$}; 
\backslash
node [below] at (bottom) {$N$}; 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
