\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normal Reaction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Normal-Reaction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

When two bodies are pressed against each other, they exert forces on each
 other.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Figure-1a"

\end_inset

 one block is kept on the other block which is kept on ground.
 Due to the gravitational force of the earth the upper block pushes the
 lower block towards the center of the earth.
 But as a common observation we find that the upper block remains at rest.
 This is only possible if there is another force exerted by the lower block
 on to the upper block which exactly balances the downward gravitational
 pull.
 This force is often called the Normal Force or the Normal Reaction.
 This force is a result of contact between bodies and arises due to the
 complicated electromagnetic interactions that take place between the bodies
 at the contact surface.
 The normal reaction is always perpendicular to the surface of the bodies
 hence the name normal.
 There are several symbols used in literature for normal reaction, most
 notably 
\begin_inset Formula $N,\,\,F_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In fig 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Figure-1a"

\end_inset

 normal reaction 
\begin_inset Formula $N=mg$
\end_inset

 whereas in the case of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Figure-1b"

\end_inset

 the normal reaction is 
\begin_inset Formula $R=mg\cos\theta.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tension force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Wrap figure
lines 0
placement o
overhang 0col%
width "50col%"
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fill [pattern=north west lines,pattern color=black!50]  (-2,1) -- (2,1)
 -- (2,1.7) -- (-2,1.7) -- cycle; 
\backslash
draw [very thick] (-2,1)--(2,1); 
\backslash
coordinate (top) at (0,1); 
\backslash
coordinate (ball) at (0,-4); 
\backslash
coordinate (bottom) at (0,-5.5); 
\backslash
draw [thick] (top) -- (ball) [very thick,-latex] -- (bottom); 
\backslash
draw[very thick,-latex] (ball) -- +(0,1.5) ; 
\backslash
draw [fill] (ball) circle (0.25); 
\backslash
node [anchor=west] (tension) at (0.1,-2.8) {$T$}; 
\backslash
node [anchor=west] (tension) at (0.1,-5.4) {$mg$}; 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tension in the string
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

The tension force is the force that is transmitted through a string, rope,
 cable or wire when it is pulled tight by forces acting from opposite ends.
 It is directed along the length of the wire and pulls equally on the objects
 on the opposite ends of the wire.
 Tension force is again a result of electromagnetic forces.
 Commonly used symbol for tension force is 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 The tension force is bi-directional along the length and acts to balance
 the external force.
 In the figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tension-force"

\end_inset

 if the sphere of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is at rest then 
\begin_inset Formula $T=mg$
\end_inset

.
 However the value of tension force depends upon the elastic properties
 of the material of the string/rope or cables.
 In most cases these elastic properties balance the applied external force
 if however the external force is large in such cases the tension may not
 be able to balance and the string/rope can break.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spring force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines] (-2,-2) grid (2,2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%draw the rectangle support
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fill [pattern=north east lines] (-2.7,-0.7) rectangle (-2,1.3); 
\backslash
draw [very thick] (-2,-0.7) -- (-2,1.3);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%define coordinates and draw the spring
\end_layout

