\begin_layout Plain Layout

%drawing the floor 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
fill [pattern=north east lines] (-2.7,-0.72) rectangle (5,-1.3); 
\backslash
draw [very thick] (-2.0,-0.72) -- (5,-0.72); 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spring force is the force exerted by a compressed or stretched spring
 upon any object that is attached to it.
 An object that compresses or stretches a spring is always acted upon by
 a force that restores the object to its rest or equilibrium position.
 The spring force is also a result of electromagnetic forces between molecules
 of the spring.
 The spring froce is given by Hooke's law.
 According to Hooke's law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
the magnitude of the spring force is directly proportional to the amount
 of stretch or compression of the spring and is always directed oppositie
 to the direction of displacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In symbols if 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 denotes the spring force and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 denotes the extension(or compression) of the spring, then according to
 Hooke's law
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\propto x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=kx;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is know as the spring constant.
 Its unit is 
\begin_inset Formula $N/m$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 denotes the stiffness of spring.
 Higher 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 value spring require larger force to produce displacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general any force that is directly proportional to displacement of object
 and in opposite directiron to displacement is known as harmonic oscillator
 force.
 Such a force causes oscillations of the object-which is a periodic motion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Friction force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force of friction is yet another type of contact force that exists between
 surfaces in contact.
 There are three kinds friction forces that exist between solid surfaces.
 Static friction, sliding friction and rolling or kinetic friction.
 The friction force is always opposite to the direction of motion.
 Static friction tends to oppose the motion of an object kept at rest.
 It is found that the friction force directly proportional to the normal
 reaction.
 In case of static friction, the maximum or the limiting value of force
 of friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{S}=\mu_{S}N;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{S}$
\end_inset

 is known as coefficient of static friction.
 Once the object starts moving the friction force decreases and is known
 as sliding friction.
 The sliding friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{K}=\mu_{K}N;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{K}$
\end_inset

 is known as coefficient of kinetic friction.
 In case of a round object rolling such as a wheel, the friction force that
 exists between the surfaces is known as rolling friction.
 The value of rolling friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{R}=\mu_{R}N.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In general it is found that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{S}>\mu_{K}>\mu_{R}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Friction force is a non-conservative force.
 Presence of friction causes the mechanical energy to decrease or convert
 into heat energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Viscosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Viscosity can be considered as a friction force that exists between fluids
 and/or fluids and solids.
 In general viscosity is a force that tends to depend upon the relative
 motion n speed of the adjacent parts of fluids.
 Such a fluid is known as viscous fluid.
 Viscosity like friction is a non-conservative force.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Uniform circular motion-centripetal force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we come across examples of motion in which an object revolves in circular
 path around a point called the center.
 A merry-go-round, a stone tied to a string when revolved, a fan rotating
 around its axis, the earth revolving around sun or the moon revolving around
 earth, an electron revolving around nucleus are all examples of motion
 known as circular motion.
 Circular motion is only possible if there exists a force that binds the
 object towards the center; such a force is therefore called the centripetal
 force.
 In uniform circular motion the speed of object remains constant while its
 direction keeps on changing; hence it is an accelerated motion, the correspondi
ng acceleration is known as centripetal acceleration.
 Centripetal force is not a new kind of force but is just a term given in
 reference to uniform circular motion.
 The centripetal force can be any of the forces previously discussed.
 For example in the case of a stone tied to string, the force that keeps
 the stone in its path is the tension force; hence tension is the centripetal
 force in this case.
 In the case of earth revolving around sun, the centripetal force is the
 gravitational force between the sun and the earth.
 In the case of the electron it is the electromagnetic force which binds
 it to the nucleus is the centripetal force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines,color=lightgray] (-2,-2) grid (2,2); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw (0,0) coordinate (origin) circle (2cm); 
\backslash
draw [thick] (origin) -- (2,0) coordinate (particle); 
\backslash
draw [fill] (particle) circle  (2pt); 
\backslash
draw [thick,-latex] (particle) -- +(0,1.5) coordinate (tangent); 
\backslash
draw [anchor=west] node at (particle) {$P$}; 
\backslash
draw [anchor=north west] node at (tangent) {$v_0$}; 
\backslash
draw [very thick,-latex] (particle) --  (1,0); 
\backslash
draw [anchor=north west] node at (1,0) {$T$}; 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the centripetal force is due to gravity we have the Newton's law of gravitati
on.
 If it is electromagnetic force we have the Coulomb's law.
 But in most cases it may not possible to find an exact formula for centripetal
 force.
 But one can still calculate the value of centripetal force based on the
 properties of the object that revolves.
 Consider a stone of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 tied to a string of length 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and is being revolved with a constant speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The formula for centripetal force is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In case of the stone as long as the stone keeps revolving the tension force
 is the centripetal force and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we observe from the frame of reference of the object the object feels
 the force which pushes it away from the center (due to inertia).
 This force is known as centrifugal force.
 The centrifugal force is not a “real” force — the tendency to fly outwards
 is observed because objects that are moving in a straight line tend to
 continue moving in a straight line.
 This is called inertia, and it makes objects resistant to the force that
 makes them move in a curve.
 The value of the centrifugal force is also given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If an object is properly rotating, both the centrifugal and centripetal
 forces will be equal, so the object will not move towards the center of
 revolution or outwards from it.
 It will maintain a constant distance from the center.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Satellite motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering 
\backslash
begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2, every node/.style={scale=1.2}]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%grid with help lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
draw [help lines] (-2,-2) grid (2,2) ;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% Drawing the Earth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw (0,0) coordinate (orig) [fill=black!30,thick] circle  (0.75) node [,anchor=n
orth] { Earth}; 
\backslash
draw (orig) [fill] circle (1pt);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% orbit of satellite 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw (orig) [thick] circle (2);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% satellite and its components 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


