\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%distances
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [thick] (orig) -- (sat); 
\backslash
draw [thick,latex-latex,dashed] (0.2,0) -- +(0,0.7) ; 
\backslash
draw (0.15,0.35) node [anchor=west] { R};
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
draw [thick,latex-latex,dashed] (0.2,0.85) -- (0.2,1.9) ; 
\backslash
draw (0.15,1.35) node [anchor=west] {h}; 
\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

The problem of satellite motion can easily be solved by making use of Newton's
 law of gravitation and centripetal force.
 Consider a satellite of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 which is to be launched at a definite height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 from the surface of the earth.
 Let mass of earth be 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and radius of earth be 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Now at this height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 the gravitational attraction due to earth must provide the centripetal
 force required to maintain the satellite in its orbit.
 In other words 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{G}=F_{C}.$
\end_inset

 If the speed of satellite is not sufficient then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}<F_{G}$
\end_inset

 and the satellite will fall to the surface of earth.
 If speed of satellite is more so that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}>F_{G}$
\end_inset

, then the satellite will escape the pull of earth.
 Thus to keep it revolving at some height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 it must be made to revolve with a definite speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 which will make 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{G}=F_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the required orbital speed then at this speed we must have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{G} & = & F_{C}\\
G\frac{Mm}{(R+h)^{2}} & = & \frac{mv^{2}}{(R+h)}\\
v^{2} & = & \frac{GM}{(R+h)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

the required speed is therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v=\sqrt{\frac{GM}{R+h}}.\label{eq:sateliite-speed}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus the satellite if launched at the required height 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 must be given this speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in order to keep it revolving in its orbit.
 We can also obtain the time period of the satellite.
 Time period 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the time taken by the satellite to complete one revolution around the
 earth.
 In one revolution the distance covered by the satellite around the earth
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi(R+h)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
T & = & \frac{\text{distance}}{\text{speed}}\\
T & = & \frac{2\pi(R+h)}{v}\\
T^{2} & = & \frac{4\pi^{2}(R+h)^{2}}{v^{2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Substituting the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sateliite-speed"

\end_inset

 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T^{2}=\frac{4\pi^{2}(R+h)^{3}}{GM}.\label{eq:time-period}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

