\backslash
draw (mid) [fill] circle (0.1);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzpicture}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a bike or car makes a turn at a road, the friction force prevents the
 bike or car from slipping off the track.
 However if the speed of the vehicle is large the friction force may not
 be sufficient to provide the necessary centripetal force.
 In that case the bike may slip.
 So the maximum safe speed can be obtained easily.
 If the mass of the bike is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and the coefficient of static friction of the track is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{S}$
\end_inset

 and radius of the turning arc is 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mu_{S}N & = & \frac{mv_{\text{safe}}^{2}}{r}\\
\mu_{S}mg & = & \frac{mv_{\text{safe}}^{2}}{r}\\
v_{\text{safe}} & = & \sqrt{\mu_{S}rg}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Concept of work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In physics the concepts of work and energy are extremely useful tools to
 solve many physical problems.
 A principle known as the conservation of energy is a central idea behind
 the happenings of any process in the entire universe.
 The idea of work or energy can be assumed to be developed parallel to the
 idea of force although we will begin the concept of work as a result of
 force.
 However it can be safely assumed that the conservation of energy can be
 used to effectively to predict the future of an event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever a force acting on a body produces a change in its position; work
 is said to be done by the force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
Work is measured by the product of the applied force and the displacement
 of the body in the direction of the force, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{work}=\text{force}\times\text{displacement parallel to force}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Work is usually denoted with 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and if denote the distance with 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W & =\vec{F}\cdot\vec{d}\label{eq:workvectoreqn}\\
W & =Fd\cos\theta.
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the force and displacement.
 Thus work is a scalar product of force and displacement.
 The SI unit of work is 
\series bold
Joule
\series default
 written in symbol as 
\series bold
J
\series default
.
 We have
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $J=Nm$
\end_inset

.

\series default
 One can easily see that when both the displacement and force are parallel
 (or anti-parallel) the work done is maximum and when force and displacement
 are mutually perpendicular; the work done is zero.
 We later learn that positive work done increases the energy and negative
 work done decreases (dissipates) the energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work done by a constant force and constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 can be calculated with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:workvectoreqn"

\end_inset

, but if during the course of the objects motion the work done keeps on
 changing or if the direction of the displacement keeps on changing, one
 must divide the motion into small enough segments and consider adding the
 work done during this small displacements (at which 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 may be treated constants) to calculate the total work done during the motion.
 In such a case the total work done may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W=\int\vec{F}\cdot\vec{dx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 denotes the small displacements in which the total displacement is broken
 into.
 Yet another way to calculate work done is through plotting the graph between
 the applied force and the displacement.
 If value of force is measured at each points of the displacement path and
 plotted on xy plane, the area covered by the force graph with the x-axis
 gives the total work done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
The energy of a body is defined as its capacity of doing work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like work energy is also a scalar quantity and the dimensions are also identical
 to that of work.
 Therefore the SI unit of energy is also joule.
 In a mechanical system energy is mainly classified as being either Kinetic
 or Potential.
 Sum of Kinetic and Potential energies is called the total mechanical energy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Kinetic energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy possessed by a body due to its motion is called its kinetic energy.
 If an object of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is moving with a (constant) speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, then the kinetic energy possessed by the body is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K=\frac{1}{2}mv^{2}\label{eq:keliner}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Just as force was related to acceleration through F = ma, so is work related
 to velocity through the Work-Energy Theorem.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{\text{net}}=\Delta K=K_{f}-K_{i}=\frac{1}{2}mv_{f}^{2}-\frac{1}{2}mv_{i}^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The net work done by all the forces on a body of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is equal to the change in kinetic energy of the body.
 Positive work done will increase the kinetic energy whereas the negative
 work done will decrease the kinetic energy of the body.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conservative forces and Potential Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the idea of work, we can classify forces as conservative or non-conserv
ative.
 A conservative force is a force which conserves the total mechanical energy
 of a body.
 A body moving under conservative force does not loose energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{multicols}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Electricity and Magnetism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{multicols}{2}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electromagnetic force is one of the fundamental forces that is very
 well understood at almost all levels.
 It was known from ancient times that if we rub objects together then they
 acquire a special thing or property due to which the objects can attract
 or repel each other.
 This special thing that the objects acquired is known as charge.
 Charge will be denoted by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and its unit is the coulomb or 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Now the property of charge must be looked as any other property of an object
 such as color, shape or even mass.
 Just like an object can possess the property of color it can possess charge.
 Now there are several key things about charge itself that we should pay
 attention to.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Charge comes in two varieties
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Traditionally termed positive and negative, the two types of charges lead
 to both the attractive and repulsive forces.
 Forces between like charges are repulsive whereas between opposite charges
 are attractive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Charge is conserved
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The total charge in an isolated system always remains the same.
 In other words charges cannot be created or destroyed.
 Charges can be transferred from one body to other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Charge is quantized
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

When we rub two objects together it is the electrons which move from one
 object to the other.
 Now the charge on an electron is 
\begin_inset Formula $e=1.6\times10^{-19}C$
\end_inset

.
 We can only transfer whole electrons on to other objects.
 It means the total charge on an object can be a multiple of the number
 of electrons charge i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=ne$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Force between two charges-Coulomb's law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coulomb a french engineer studied the forces between charged objects for
 several years and found a formula for the force between them.
 He measured the force to be proportional to the product of charges and
 inversely proportional to the square of the distance between the charges.
 In symbols if the charges are labeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 and if the distance between them is 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename coulombs.pdf
	scale 200
	BoundingBox 150bp 10bp 250bp 48bp

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Coulomb's law
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{0} & \propto\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}\\
F_{0} & =\frac{kq_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=9\times10^{9}\,Nm^{2}/C^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an experimentally measured value.
 If the value of force is positive then it denotes repuslive force and attractiv
e if negative.
 In this formula it is assumed that the charges are placed in vacuum or
 air.
 If instead we place any medium such as a paper in between the charges,
 the force between the charges reduces by some factor.
 If we denote the vacuum force by 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

 then the force in a medium may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{1}=\frac{F_{0}}{\epsilon_{r}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{r}$
\end_inset

 by which the force reduces depends upon the type of material medium placed
 between the charges.
 It is a pure number and commonly know as dielectric constant of the material.
 It is also know as the relative permittivity of the medium.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{r}=1$
\end_inset

 for air.
 The constant 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 can further be written in terms of another fundamental constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}=8.8\times10^{-12}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}/Nm^{2}$
\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus we get for vacuum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{0}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and for medium 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{1}=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}\epsilon_{r}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The product 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}\epsilon_{r}=\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is known as the permittivity (absolute permittivity) of the medium.
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{r}=\frac{\epsilon}{\epsilon_{0}}=\frac{F_{0}}{F_{1}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electric Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we are given magnets to play with we get fascinated by the way they
 exert forces onto one another even at a distance without any contact.
 This kind of non-contact behaviour of forces used to puzzle the great minds
 of Newton and Coulomb as well, since through a number of experiments we
 have come to know that we need some kind of contact to exert forces.
 Thus it was difficult for them to understand a force without contact.
 So in order to restore the contact idea, it was thought that the charges
 do exert forces via some kind of invisible contact.
 They thought that the charges gave some invisible property to the space
 around them due to which if any other charge entered into their proximity
 will experience the force of electricity.
 This invisible property is known as the Field.
 So every charge produces its own field known as the electric field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically a field (of any charge distribution) is a function of position
 and time; i.e.
 its value changes from point to point and also with time.
 Consider a situation in which some charge is kept hidden in a box.
 If we ask a question whether a charge exists within the box or not? This
 kind of question can not be answered just by looking at the box (since
 charge does not glow).
 In order to answer this question one can bring another charge and place
 it outside the box but near the box and measure the force (if any) acting
 onto the charge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fieldtest43.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Testing the presence of charge
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

If we find that this charge experiences some force then we can infer that
 the box contains some charge.
 In this case we can see that the charge within the box produces One can
 take the analogy of a perfume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Coulomb's law, electric field, electric potential, application for single
 charge and dipole, Gauss' law and its applications, Concept of magnetic
 field, Ampere's circuital law and its applications(wire, solenoid, toroid),
 Lorentz force, Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction, experiments,
 lenz law, self and mutual induction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electric field lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electric field lines are a convenient way to visualise the presence of fields.
 The field lines can be drawn by imagining a curve drawn along the path
 followed by a positive charge.
 Thus the field lines are imaginary curves along which a positive charge
 would tend to move if it were free to do so.
 Lets take some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field lines are diverging (going outwards) from single positive charge
 and converging (going inwards) for a single negative charge.
\end_layout

