\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electric field of a dipole
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A system of two equal but opposite charges separated by a small distance
 are known as a dipole.
 A dipole is electrically neutral yet in the proximity of a dipole the field
 of the dipole at any point may not be zero since the nearness of any one
 charge will contribute more field than the other.
 This causes certain residual field to be generated.
 The properties of this residual field are important not just for academic
 purpose but also for practical purpose since many molecules can be treated
 as dipoles to a good approximation.
 Just as value of charge denotes the strength of electric field produced
 by a single charge, in case of a dipole a related physical quantity called
 the dipole moment is of great significance.
 The symbol used for dipole moment is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=2aq.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Axis passing through the line joining the charges is known as the axis of
 the dipole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Axial point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine a point at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 from the center of the dipole situated on the axis of the dipole, an axial
 point.
 We are interested in calculating the field produced by this dipole at this
 location.
 The net field at this point will be just the sum of the fields due to the
 positive and the negative charges.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{\text{axial}}=E_{+q}+E_{-q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, we can write the formulae for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{+q}$
\end_inset

 and and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{-q}$
\end_inset

 by making use of the formula of a field due to a single charge, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{+q}=\frac{kq}{\left(r-a\right)^{2}}\,\,\,\,\text{and}\,\,\,\,E_{-q}=\frac{kq}{\left(r+a\right)^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{\text{axial}} & =\frac{kq}{\left(r-a\right)^{2}}-\frac{kq}{\left(r+a\right)^{2}}\\
E_{\text{axial}} & =\frac{k\left(4aq\right)r}{\left(r^{2}-a^{2}\right)^{2}}\\
E_{\text{axial}} & =k\frac{2pr}{\left(r^{2}-a^{2}\right)^{2}}\label{eq:dipole_axial}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dipole_axial"

\end_inset

 gives the value of the electric field for a dipole.
 If the point of observation lies far away from the tiny dipole i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg a$
\end_inset

, then neglecting 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in the denominator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{\text{axial}} & =k\frac{2pr}{r^{4}}\\
E_{\text{axial}} & =k\frac{2p}{r^{3}};
\end{align}

\end_inset

the equation says that the dipole field falls off as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r^{3}$
\end_inset

 from the charge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{tikzpicture} %
\backslash
draw [help lines] (-2,-1) grid (7,1);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
coordinate (origin) at (0,0); 
\backslash
coordinate (left) at (-1.5,0); 
\backslash
coordinate (right) at (1.5,0); 
\backslash
coordinate (point) at (6,0);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shade [ball color=black!1] (left) circle (0.4cm) node (pos) {$-q$}; 
\backslash
shade [ball color=black!1] (right) circle (0.4cm) node (neg) {$+q$}; 
\backslash
draw [fill] (point) circle (0.05); 
\backslash
