\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now the point to be located at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 on the line passing through the center of the dipole and perperndicular
 to its axis i.e.
 its perpendicular bisector.
 Since the point of observation now lies at an eqaul distance from both
 the charges the fields of both the charges have same magnitude
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{+q}=E_{-q}=\frac{kq}{(r+a)^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

But as can be seen from the diagram; only the vertically downward components
 contribute to the total field whereas horizontal components being equal
 and opposite cancel out, thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{\text{pb}} & =E_{+Q}\cos\theta+E_{-Q}\cos\theta\\
 & =2E_{+Q}\cos\theta
\end{align}

\end_inset

From the diagram we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\cos\theta=\frac{a}{\sqrt{r^{2}+z^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and so we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
E_{\text{pb}} & =2\frac{kq}{\left(r+a\right)^{2}}\times\frac{a}{\sqrt{r^{2}+z^{2}}}\\
E_{\text{pb}} & =\frac{\left(2aq\right)k}{\left(r^{2}+a^{2}\right)^{3/2}}\\
E_{\text{pb}} & =\frac{pk}{\left(r^{2}+a^{2}\right)^{3/2}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

If the point of observation lies far away i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gg a$
\end_inset

 then neglecting 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

 in above equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\text{pb}}=\frac{pk}{r^{3}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electrostatic potential energy and potential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Till now the discussion has been based on the idea of force and field (force
 per unit charge).
 In mechanics we had an alternative but equivalent approach based on energy
 that allowed us to solve many problems without going into complicated calculati
ons involving forces.
 The electric force is also a conservative force.
 Therefore a natural question arises that if we have a collection of charges
 then what is the potential energy associated with it.
 This can be calculated by just calculating the work required to assemble
 the collection of charges.
 Let us start with the simplest configuration of collection of charges i.e.
 a pair of charges.
 Suppose we have two positive charges 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We shall treat the charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 as the source charge and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 as the test charge.
 Suppose initially the test charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 is at a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 from the source charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and we want to bring it closer and place it at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 For this we will have to do some work against the electric force of repulsion.
 The work done is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W=F\times d\label{eq:workdoneele}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

now here we can write for the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=y-x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.
 But the value of force changes on the entire path.
 For example the value of forces at the intial and final points are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{x}=\frac{kqq_{1}}{x^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{y}=\frac{kqq_{1}}{y^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So which of these should we use in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:workdoneele"

\end_inset

.
 The thing is that we have to take some kind of average of these two values.
 In this case since the force changes as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r^{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 as a geometric progression we can take a geometric average of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{y}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F & =\sqrt{F_{x}F_{y}}\\
 & =\frac{kqq_{1}}{xy}
\end{align}

\end_inset

, and we have for 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:workdoneele"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
W & =\frac{kqq_{1}}{xy}\cdot\left(y-x\right)\\
W & =kqq_{1}\left(\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{y}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset

This work done equals the change in potential energy
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W=\Delta U=U_{x}-U_{y}=kqq_{1}\left(\frac{1}{x}-\frac{1}{y}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus we can write for the potential energy of the system of source charge
 and test charge separated by distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\frac{kqq_{1}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From the potential energy it is easy to define potential.
 The potential at a point located at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 due to a single source charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is obtained by calculating the work done in bringing a unit positive (test)
 charge from infinity and placing it at 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 In other words it is the potential energy per unit charge, thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V=\frac{W}{q_{1}}=\frac{U}{q_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus for a single (source) charge the potential at any distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V=\frac{kq}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Unlike electric field potential is a scalar quantity.
 Its value is positive for a positive source charge and negative for a negative
 source charge.
 When we have a collection of charges the potential at a point is just the
 algebraic sum of potentials due to individual charges at respective distances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Potential of a dipole
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Flux, Gauss' law and its applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flux of an electric field through any surface area is the number of
 field lines that pass through the area.
 If we have a closed surface that encloses a volume, then the total flux
 is the number of field lines entering minus the number of field lines leaving
 the surface.
 The field lines entering is the influx whereas those leaving is the out
 flux.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{flux}=\text{in flux}-\text{out flux}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

