\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Electric current
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flow of charge from one point to the other is termed as electric current.
 Charges can be put in motion by creating a potential difference or voltage.
 Traditionally the motion of charges from higher potential(voltage) to lower
 potential(voltage) is termed as current and it is due to the movement of
 positive charges.
 However in actual circuits current is due to the motion of negatively charged
 electrons from lower potential to higher potential.
 In general only conductors allow for easy movement of charges due to the
 presence of fee electrons.
 Thus if we apply some potential difference across the ends of a conductor
 then current through the conductor is defined as the amount of (positive)
 charges that flow about a cross section in unit time,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=\frac{Q}{t}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The SI unit of current is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{J.s^{-1}}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 also known as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{Ampere} or 
\backslash
si{A}.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
EMF of a cell
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electromotive force or EMF of a cell is defined as the work done by
 the cell on to the charges to create a potential difference across its
 plates.
 It is numerically equal to the voltage across the plates of a cell when
 no current flows through it.
 Its unit is the same as that of potential difference i.e.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{V}.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ohm's law, Resistance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ohm's law is a relationship between the current flowing through a conductor
 and the voltage applied across its ends.
 It states that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

At constant temperature, the current passing through a conductor is directly
 proportional to the voltage applied across its ends
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I & \propto V\\
V & =IR
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=V/I$
\end_inset

 is defined as the resistance of the conductor.
 Its unit is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{V/A}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 known as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{Ohm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
si{
\backslash
ohm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resistivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resistance of a conductor depends on various factors including temperature.
 It is found that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\propto l\,\,\text{length of conductor}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\propto\frac{1}{A}\,\,\text{area of conductor}.
\]

\end_inset

 Thus we can write the resistance of the conductor as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=\rho\frac{l}{A}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is known as the resistivity of a conductor.
 
\end_layout

